Definition
-	IPv6 is designed to be the successor to IPv4. IPv6 has a larger 128-bit address space, providing 340 undecillion (i.e., 340 followed by 36 zeroes) possible addresses. However, IPv6 is more than just larger addresses.

Advantages
-	IPv6 provides a massive amount of address spaces ranging up to 340 undecillion addresses compared to IPv4. It also eliminated the need for NAT and allowing direct end-to-end connectivity.
-	Almost all devices have different IPv6 addresses.

Disadvantages:
-	IPv4 and IPv6 cannot communicate directly, requiring transition mechanism.
-	It seems, it’s also more complex and costly to make than IPv4.

